EXPERIMENT: D5_SOS1_EXTENDED_EGFR_NSCLC_v1
DATE: 2026-06-06
STATUS: pre-registered
EXTENDS: D3_EGFR_MUTANT_NSCLC (pre-reg 8dc23d5)
DATASET: PRISM Repurposing 20Q2 Secondary Screen (same as D3)
CELL LINES: same 10 EGFR-dep lines as D3_EGFR_MUTANT_NSCLC

MOTIVATION:
SOS1 (delta_r = +0.0954) is the strongest structural DAMPER in the EGFR-NSCLC
signaling network (examples/egfr_nsclc_signaling.json, 23 items). In the
context-dependence framework, DAMPER = structural target in ODS-regime cancers.
BI-3406 (Boehringer Ingelheim SOS1 inhibitor, clinical trials NCT04973163) is
NOT in PRISM 20Q2. This creates a structural drug discovery gap: our best
structural target has no pharmacological probe in the available screen.

EXTENSION FROM D3:
D3_EGFR_MUTANT_NSCLC tested 5 curated drugs (trametinib, erlotinib, everolimus,
copanlisib, MK-2206) targeting MEK1, EGFR, mTOR, PI3K, AKT1.
D5 extends to ALL available PRISM drugs targeting EGFR-NSCLC network proteins,
including drug classes not tested in D3:
- JAK2 inhibitors (ruxolitinib, baricitinib, AZD1480, TG-101348, pacritinib)
  JAK2 delta_r = -0.032 in EGFR-NSCLC (ANCHOR)
- ERK1 inhibitor (SCH772984/ulixertinib/LY3214996)
  ERK1 delta_r = -0.070 in EGFR-NSCLC (strongest ANCHOR)
- BRAF inhibitors (vemurafenib, dabrafenib, PLX-4720)
  BRAF delta_r = -0.024 (ANCHOR)
- Additional EGFR/mTOR/PI3K/AKT/MEK1 drugs beyond D3's single representative

PRIMARY HYPOTHESIS (H1, CONFIRMATORY):
The Spearman rank correlation r(delta_r, mean_LFC) observed in D3 (r=-1.000, n=5)
remains statistically significant (p < 0.05) when extended to the full PRISM
drug set mapped to EGFR-NSCLC network proteins (estimated n=8-12 target proteins
with available drugs).

Direction: negative (more negative delta_r = stronger anchor = less growth =
more negative LFC = stronger killing). Confirmed negative in D3 (anchor proteins
are more killable when targeted in this ODS-like cancer).

SECONDARY HYPOTHESIS (H2, EXPLORATORY):
ERK1 inhibitors (delta_r = -0.070, strongest anchor) show more negative mean LFC
than AKT1 inhibitors (delta_r = -0.025) in EGFR-dep NSCLC lines.
If H2 confirmed: anchors are better targets in ODS-regime cancers, contra the
classical ODS model. If denied: ODS model holds (dampers are the targets).

STRUCTURAL DRUG GAP DOCUMENTATION:
SOS1 (delta_r = +0.0954) — NO DRUG in PRISM 20Q2
GRB2 (delta_r = +0.0438) — NO DRUG in PRISM 20Q2
PTEN (delta_r = +0.0116) — tumor suppressor, no pharmacological activator
RAS  (delta_r = +0.0725) — only farnesyltransferase proxy (lonafarnib);
                            no direct RAS inhibitor in PRISM 20Q2
SOS1 is the #1 structural druggability gap in EGFR-NSCLC.

PROSPECTIVE PREDICTION:
BI-3406 (or any clinical SOS1 inhibitor) tested in EGFR-dep NSCLC lines should
show mean LFC between 0 and +0.20 (positive: growth restoration, not killing).
Reason: SOS1 is a DAMPER — removing it disrupts structural balance. Drugs that
restore SOS1 function (if SOS1-gain-of-function were possible) would be
therapeutic. SOS1 INHIBITORS would be counterproductive by ODS logic.
This is the SOS1 paradox: strongest structural target predicts drug FAILURE.
Alternative framing: SOS1 inhibitors may work by a non-structural mechanism
(blocking RAS-GEF exchange), and this may conflict with structural prediction.
RESOLUTION: empirical test when BI-3406 enters a future screen.

